So I am curious to understand the rationale, it still looks a lot like fib specific?
Or is it an issue of an "interface" being dependent upon "fib" instead of the other way around?

Patch Set 3:

> Patch Set 3:
> 
> (5 comments)
> 
> So I am curious to understand the rationale, it still looks a lot like fib specific?
> Or is it an issue of an "interface" being dependent upon "fib" instead of the other way around?

my intent is to move the FIB's child-parent dependency tracking out of FIB and into a common location. That way it can be used by object outside of the FIB without them needing to express a code-dependency on FIB. My ultimate goal (and this is in the commit at the top of this chain) is to use this dependency tracking on an interface, that is add a dep_t to a vent_sw_interface_t so objects can track it directly.
Forming direct child-parent relationships, and thus having events on the parent propagate directly back to only those objects that are affected, is a more efficient and thus more scalable notification mechanism. The present notification mechanism for interfaces is callback function based, so multiple sub-systems are notified for each interface update and they all do work to find their own affect objects.

I am not fond of this: we should certainly not have a specific case hardcoded for certain interfaces. If needs be, it should be a parameter at creation time, eg. add a parameter to pass this tx_burst value.
Now, if I understand correctly, the issue is that when we ring the doorbell, veth backend will only process up to 16 descriptors before going back to sleep. Otherwise it looks like a bug in the kernel: there are packets to process, but veth just left them there.
